The influence of the incubation time on the cell internalization of AS1411-CLT1-Gd-CDs was then investigated. The results demonstrated the cell membrane was strongly lit up after very short incubation periods (0.5 h). When the incubation time was increased to 2 h, a majority of nanoparticles could enter the cells. Both the cell membrane and cell internal showed strong fluorescence (Fig. 3
                        ). We proposed that the fast uptake of AS1411-CLT1-Gd-CDs could be attributed to the small size (less than10 nm) and ligand-mediated endocytosis of the nanoprobes. On the contrary, the HK-2 normal cells displayed relatively weak fluorescence at all the test times, indicating that AS1411-CLT1-Gd-CDs have specificity to cancer cells. Such results were further proven by quantitative analysis. The fluorescence intensity of 786-O cells treated with AS1411-CLT1-Gd-CDs increased more than 60% in just half an hour and increased slowly with time (Fig. 4
                        A). The fluorescence increment is much greater than that of HK-2 cells under the same conditions. The fluorescence intensity of the 786-O cells after treatment with AS1411-CLT1-Gd-CDs for 2 h was 2.3-fold than that of the treated HK-2 cells (Fig. 4B and C). Therefore, the probes can be characterized with high specificity, and they are capable of distinguishing cancer cells from normal cells.
